>>114998411
I love 90s ads and promos.
There's just this sense of fear and loathing in them.
They knew that the audience was:
>kids, who like weird shit because they're kids
>teens and young adults who were all high as fuck

You don't even get close to that sort of awareness in advertisement, because ceos now have such a warped perception of their audience and such a condescending "you will like this whether you like it or not" tone to their marketing now.
In the past, marketing wasn't indoctrination, it was a snake selling you an apple from the vine and people were frank about it because they realised that this was just how it was in reality.

Now it's all about pretending to be perfect and infallible. That's why you have this fucked up shit with pharma companies forcing their marketing down your throat to the point of controlling censorship now.
In the past that was just unthinkable when I was a kid.
People say it's always been like that, but I disagree. You look at ads from the 90s and people were fully frank about their nature as a snake oil salesmen in most things because that's just simply how free markets work and how we get new innovations. It's clumsy and rough. But at least it's not mere propaganda. Marketing is marketing, not propaganda. People don't understand how that is nowadays.

>>115002134
Coming from someone who has learned DJing and done shows and has been learning production for three years, it's not comparable at all. It's going to take a lot more time to get better at production than learning how to mix that I can't recommend learning how to DJ unless you really have a passion for it. You're way better off learning how DAWs and synthesizers work if you want to produce UKG, the DJing can wait until later.

One of the only few positives I can think of when it comes to learning how to DJ from a production standpoint is that it forces you to listen to a lot of music which helps you develop your taste on what good and bad music is, but you should already be doing that if you're a fan of music. Beyond that it's good from a marketing standpoint, but that shouldn't matter until you become a real artist. Just pick up reaper and vital and go search on youtube for a few tutorials to get you started on your journey.

Same anon from >>115004586 here, honestly learning theory was one of the easier parts of learning music production in my own experience. The amount of theory you need for dance music production is pretty surface level and watching youtube videos got me most of the way there.

Getting used to a DAW though is another challenge, and finding the right DAW for you does help. I tried FL for a few hours and I absolutely hated the UI, but I tried out Ableton later on and I really liked how similar it felt to like a word processor, it just clicked with me.

I can't really recommend specific courses, I've just been watching five or six different youtube channels talk about music production for the past two years and I picked up different tips and tricks from these creators as I went along. It was pretty difficult starting out and it still is challenging trying to recreate music from my favorite genres, but it gets easier every day you keep doing it.

What Leo did was basically on the shoulders of hundreds of AV/Radio nerds before him. Remember, the Fender Broadcaster/Telecaster was made almost exclusively for the Television/Film industry because Audio engineers working just north of Orange County needed to capture the sound of a guitar with as little feedback as possible, and they needed to capture guitar live for the then-new Late Night Talk shows starting to appear on TV sets. It's weird to imagine the type of mindset LeoFender was in under this context. All in all the electric guitar hasn't really changed all that much. A modern Fender Tele feels just like a piece of 1950s radio equipment, and I mean that in a good way.

The fact of the matter is that coffee, and caffeine for that matter, is one of the mildest stimulants there is. Now compare this to actual drugs (or stimulants). 4 weeks of prescribed benzos and tapering it according with the orders of doctor resulted in 4-6 months of physical withdrawal hell and agony, every day felt like your worst hangover and after 180 days you started to feel normal.

Coffee is so mild drug and stim that it is totally irrelevant do you drink it or not. Totally irrelevant, even a habit of +12 cups a day for 2 decades straight will give you at most a week long withdrawal symptoms.

2013 was like 3 whole cultural eras away from the current one. "Indie," referring to any kind of small-scale but notable industry actually making, selling, and marketing decent music in some decent level of quantity, has been dead since 2015. That year pitchfork got bought by conde nast, the last of the new york showspaces were destroyed, and streaming replaced cd's and itunes. The last on is important because it completely gutted artist revenues from everything besides merch and live shows. No one could sell records anymore, and the entire industry kind of dried up. The next year of course a bunch of political shit happened, everything got acrimonious, and also there was the ghost ship warehouse fire which killed over 30 people. Within about 3 years people making actual music were pretty much left with no way to break through as unknown artists, or to make money from their music. Then the pandemic raped touring for 2 years. The entire music industry outside of major celebrities is really hard-up. Terrible time to be a musician. Even 10 years ago, when it was a 'hipster' scene that people shat on, it was thriving in comparision. People made fun of it but in hindsight it's much better than nothing at all except political shrieking. At least the obnoxious hipsters sometimes made actual music. Now it's almost extinct. The fact that so many books still name the Beatles as "the greatest or most significant or most influential" rock band ever only tells you how far rock music still is from becoming a serious art. Jazz critics have long recognized that the greatest jazz musicians of all times are Duke Ellington and John Coltrane, who were not the most famous or richest or best sellers of their times, let alone of all times. The Beatles sold more than anyone else (not true, by the way), therefore they must have been the greatest. Jazz critics grow up listening to a lot of jazz music of the past, classical critics grow up listening to a lot of classical music of the past. Rock critics are often totally ignorant of the rock music of the past, they barely know the best sellers. No wonder they will think that the Beatles did anything worthy of being saved.

posts.com:
I've noticed that the defining albums of genres are almost never the best.

Take the Sex Pistols for punk rock, and Blur's Parklife for Britpop. The Sex Pistols are the most concise summation of everything punk is. The sneering vocal. The lose, melodic guitar style, lifted from the Dolls. The cutting lyrics. The image. There isn't a better summary. The Damned come close, but the vocals are a little too goth, the instruments a little too garage (though it's also a way, way better album). Crass were a little too artsy and experimental. You could say the Sex Pistols were just following New Yorkers like Richard Hell and the Ramones, but the Ramones were as much power pop as anything, and many new wavers didn't even realize their punk 'cred, while Richard Hell was way more experimental and Beat poet than most punk. Yet all the bands I mentioned who are less defining of punk, are also much, much more interesting artists. Better artists.

Similarly, take Blur's Parklife. It defines exactly what Britpop is. It's bright, bouncy, theatrical, socially incisive, has that 90s London cool. It's also an extremely annoying album. Oasis wrote better songs, but were more straightforwardly rock. Suede, Pulp, and Supergrass were way more experimental, veering out of Britpop territory, yet all are better artists. But none define Britpop as much as Blur on Parklife. Which IMO is actually one of their weakest albums.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Remaking because it 404'd. A comment on Britpop: I would say despite the diversity and inadequacy of the term, I do think there's a place for it. To me, it's when British indie transitioned from a generally lo-fi, jangly sound in the late 80s, to a more mainstream-ready, cleanly produced, stylish sound.

Also, this is minor, but somebody compared Suede to Siouxsie & The Banshees, and I have to say, that's about the worst influence comparison I've ever seen. Suede definitely have a post-punk element, and Anderson and Siouxsie both let single vocal notes ring out a lot, but other than that, there's nothing there.

>>115013545
the lows are actually fine i think. The other effects would still be good though. If you're just messing around it's not a big deal ya know but it might make it sound better.

Basically that sort of effects "chain" is common in contemporary music (Compressor + Chorus + Delay + Reverb), like if you listen to Lil Peep it's very obvious there are a lot of effects to smooth out his voice. It's just to fill out the track and make it sound less like a raw microphone. You could also just record 2 or 3 vocal tracks on top of each other, but you would have to sing pretty accurately to match the autotune notes.

Quick rundown of effects and what they do:
Compressor: Makes quiet things louder and louder things quieter. The level where things get quieter/louder is the "Threshold", and the amount of how quiet/loud they get is the Ratio
Chorus: Makes things sound like a chorus, this is done by copying a sound and slightly detuning it
Delay: pretty self explanatory, adds an echo. try different time/feedback and see what sounds good
Reverb: makes things sound like they're in a room or a big chamber

1. White Album
2. A Hard Day's Night
3. Sgt. Pepper's
4. Magical Mystery Tour

And I feel any of these four are reasonably interchangeable but I feel these are their absolute best.

5. Help!
6. Abbey Road
7. Revolver

It's my personal preference for pop songwriting, but yes I know that Good Day Sunshine, I'm Only Sleeping, Eleanor Rigby, and Tomorrow Never Knows are generally considered greater songs than Help!, You've Got To Hide Your Love Away, It's Only Love, You Like Me Too Much, and songs like that.

8. Rubber Soul
9. With The Beatles
10. Beatles For Sale
11. Let it Be
12. Please Please Me
13. Yellow Submarine

I already know that Rubber Soul has In My Life, Drive My Car, Norwegian Wood, and Think For Yourself, and so most would place it higher. It's just my preference and to be honest I enjoy With The Beatles more than Rubber Soul, I think. Beatles For Sale's pop songs are also brilliant, like "Every Little Thing", "No Reply", "Eight Days A Week" are great and v m up my alley.

It's a zeuhl chart. Zeuhl is a subgenre of prog that is characterized by operatic, booming vocals often in made up languages, aggressive, chaotic and frantic sounding composition similar to brutal prog and free jazz. Personally, I love zeuhl and you should take a listen to a bunch of these albums. If you decide to take a listen, you gotta listen to MAGMA (at least Mekanik Destruktiw Kommandoh), Koenji Hyakkei, Ruins, ZAO, Corima, eX-Girl, Amygdala and Eskaton. Have fun.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>115013293
Not at all, really. In the 00s, the British bands of the garage rock revival were basically Britpop bands, like The Libertines and the Arctic Monkeys.

Progressives have been mad at Morrissey for about 30 years now, but I would actually say there's a strongly progressive, anti-racist element to Morrissey's politics. For example, on that album National Front Disco is pretty much an indictment of right wing nationalism. But Morrissey also has a love of British culture, so it seems like there's a real struggle between his progressive tendencies and his culturally conservative ones. That tension between the left and right within him is really interesting. It's also something I can sympathize with, though I'm more explicitly left wing, at least economically. I find workers' empowerment and self-ownership a very important concept, and I admire leftist thinkers like Yanis Varoufakis. I quite like Oscar Wilde's goal of individualist socialism. However, I'm also influenced by conservative Roger Scruton's demand for the preservation of culture and beauty, since there is a greatness and utility to it. Denying that fundamentally conservative approach to the preservation of culture is too nihilistic for me.

>>115013672
I'm a Millennial, and I'm not sure I feel that way. I think mine may have been the last generation where rock was the mainstream music, but I also suspect it will return, even if it's more alongside hip hop, electronic, pop, etc. (and there's nothing wrong with that). I would say the key differences between Millennials and Gen Z are that we're defined by the emergence of the internet's cultural dominance, while that's all Gen Z have ever known. Because of that we're less addicted to tech than Gen Z, and less attached to apps, influencers, etc. - it's all fairly uninteresting, especially TikTok. However, I would also say Gen Z is more naturally skilled with it, and I know there are teens who know a lot more coding than I do because they learn it in school. That's a real asset, and given how quickly tech is advancing, I'm honestly concerned by how out of touch I may be with tech when I'm in my 60s.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>115013747
>There is nothing new under the sun
I don't really believe that. I do think culture is ephemeral, but I'd also say it's constantly changing and evolving. For example, mod could've only happened in the 60s, because it was a reaction against their parents' WW2 nostalgia, and it was a bit about embracing pop art. In music, I would actually say form follows function, in the sense that it's always evolved based on technology and socioeconomic function. Baroque music sounds the way it does because it was commissioned for social functions. Classical sounds the way it does because it was commissioned for the music itself. Classical evolved tremendously when the harpsichord evolved into the piano. When ex-slaves got guitars and turned work songs into personal confessions, we got blues. When there was guitar distortion, we got contemporary rock music. When Jamaican immigrants introduced dub reggae to New York Beat poetry, we got hip hop. Each of these things were culturally and technologically specific to their time. But the time is constantly changing, and culture and art reflect that. Nostalgia is the failure to keep up.

Exhilarating. Every backpack nerd and underground hip-hop geek freaked the fuck out over it. Sure- with a large enough population and, for every obscure or niche characteristic there is bound to be those who find it appealing and/or attractive. After all, some people like scat.
If we remove subjectivity from the equation, however, and focus on what is objectively true, it's simple and true. For every thing that lives, also dies, and has a period or time in it's life in which it is objectively at its peak, with observable physical characteristics being a manifestation used to represent or advertise this state.
Forget people, we see this elsewhere in nature. Take fruit as an example. Of course, i acknowledge that there will always be exceptions, but generally speaking, people do not pick or eat fruit when it is unripe or immature. Nor do we eat that same fruit when it is rotten. There are physical characteristic that allow us to determine when said fruit is ripe, IE. in it's prime. Just as a tree has different stages, from seedling to sapling and beyond, there is a period when that tree is also in bloom, at it's most beautiful and appealing. Without exhausting the list of EVERY living species on the entire planet, i think it is safe to say this cycle, of being before ones prime, in the midst of it or after, is applicable to most if not ALL life and humans are no exception. Outside of what is subjective, there is objective physical beauty and claiming i am "delusional" for saying so or that it is "fake shit" etc., is absurd.
FOr Yes, of course different people find different things attractive, after all, some people are attracted to scat. For every obscure or benign trait, with a large enough population there is bound to be those who find those traits "attractive".
Being, however, that we as human beings are not exempt from the cycle of life.

>>114974347
Bowie has several GREAT albums. My favorite is Station To Station but I'm not married to it, I could easily listen to any of his classic-era albums and be edified.

He did have a late-career decline, like many artists do. His albums after Let's Dance tend toward the contrived. Except what he did with Tin Machine, which was excellent.

Still, anything Bowie put out from 1970-1983 is considered all-time classic rock, and rightfully so. Interesting sidenote, unlike most musicians Bowie didn't have a "sophomore slump." His first eponymous release is actually his worst album, after that he simply got better and better, consistently, until Scary Monsters. Bowie was a true artist, I would LOVE to be a musical novice just starting to explore his catalog, great memories, great music.

New anon jumping in.
Keep in mind Pin Ups primary motivation for being made was to get the record company off Bowie's back while he was recuperating from touring and his manager was going through financial negotiations with the company. If there was any album which Bowie could be accused of shitting out, this would be it.

Now, is it terrible for what it is, essentially just Bowie covering songs that influenced him in his glam style with no greater pretension?
IMHO It could have been significantly better with minimal investment if Bowie went with songs that complemented his glam style better. "See Emily Play" is the strongest cover IMHO, plays the feel of the original well. Meanwhile, "Shapes of Things" obliterates the original feeling with the timbre and vocal choice, and every effect tacked on takes away from the song as a whole.

So while I never have much desire to listen to it, I think calling it a competent fluff album that served a practical purpose in its time is a reasonable take.

Let's clarify things. I am the most knowledgable among you, and here's what it is regarding Bowie.

He had a classic era in which he could do no wrong, everything he put out was absolutely art of the highest integrity. That period ran from Man Who Sold The World to Let's Dance.

But Bowie was also a narcissist. He KNEW he was musically irrelevant but he DESIRED the spotlight. So he continued to put out albums after Let's Dance, which should have been his magnum opus.

Fine. Bowie is a huge, important musical icon. He was totally entitled to put out music into his middle age. We didn't HAVE TO buy it or even listen to it. Of course, we did, because it was Bowie. But it was never mandatory.

Did Bowie damage his legacy by issuing a bunch of garbage late in his career? Absolutely not. Unlike other artists, we KNOW Bowie, and we KNOW that...this...isn't his best work, it's just work.

So all is forgiven for David Bowie. Yet somehow there are absolute mouth-breathing morons on this forum trying to defend his shitty late-career output like it's their fucking job. Okay. Like, seriously, WHATEVER. But don't go acting all self-righteous and shit, dudes, we KNOW you're the dipshits.

posts.com:
A terrible metal album by a punk band that once had a cool sound.

I'd actually compare Discharge's decline on it to The Jesus and Mary Chain's decline after Psychocandy, in that what made the JAMC and Discharge great bands was a simple dynamic involving noise. With the JAMC, it was combining pop songcraft and beautiful melodies with ear piercing feedback. With Discharge, it was combining Crass-style political ranting with thick, heavy guitars. In both cases, it sounded amazing. But take the noise away from the JAMC, and what was left was a fairly meh alternative rock band. Take the thick, heavy guitars away from Discharge, and what was left was incompetence. What makes Grave New World worse is that they weren't just incompetent, they also had a comically awful attempt at a high metal vocal.

The obvious comparison is Celtic Frost's glam metal material, but I also think it's a bad comparison, because I'd actually argue Celtic Frost's glam metal material isn't bad. Celtic Frost were a really good band, and on those albums they still sound like themselves, just with glam metal elements. Discharge is different, because without their signature sound, they weren't a good band. A Better comparison would be TSOL's awful groovy butt rock glam metal, though even that was done more competently.
